{{Infobox journalist | name = Michelle Lang | image= Michelle Lang.jpg | caption = | birthname = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1975|01|31|df=yes}} | birth_place = [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], [[Canada]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2009|12|30|1975|01|31|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Kandahar]], [[Afghanistan]] | education = | occupation = Reporter | alias = | title = | family = | spouse = | domestic_partner = | children = | relatives = | ethnicity = | religion = | salary = | networth = | credits = ''[[Calgary Herald]]'' | agent = | URL = }} '''Michelle Justine Lang''' (31 January 1975 in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] â 30 December 2009 in [[Kandahar]], [[Afghanistan]]) was a ''[[Calgary Herald]]'' reporter and the first [[Canada|Canadian]] journalist to die in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001âpresent)|War in Afghanistan]].<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.torontosun.com/news/canada/2010/01/04/12337131-sun.html | title=Hundreds honour heroes - Four soldiers, journalist repatriated in emotional ceremony at CFB Trenton | first=Jason | last=Miller | publisher=''[[Toronto Sun]]'' | date=4 January 2010 | accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref>
==Career== Born and raised in Vancouver, Lang was an alumnus of [[Magee Secondary School]] and [[Simon Fraser University]]. Her first job as a reporter was at the ''[[Prince George Free Press]].'' She later moved on to ''Moose Jaw Times Herald'' and the ''[[Regina Leader-Post]]'', then moved to [[Calgary]] to become a print journalist for the ''Calgary Herald''. She won a [[National Newspaper Awards|National Newspaper Award]] in 2008 for best [[beat reporting]],<ref>{{cite web | title=List of winners since 1949 | publisher=[[National Newspaper Awards]] | url=http://www.nna-ccj.ca/wordpress_dev/wordpress/?page_id=64&lang=en | accessdate=2011-10-15 }}</ref> for her reporting on on national and provincial health-care issues.<ref>{{cite web |title=NNA winner at â09 gala in Montreal dies in Afghanistan blast |publisher=[[National Newspaper Awards]] |url=http://www.nna-ccj.ca/wordpress_dev/wordpress/?p=888&lang=en |accessdate=2011-10-20}}</ref>
==Death== Lang was on a six-week assignment to Afghanistan for the ''Herald'' and ''[[Canwest News Service]]''<ref>{{cite news |url=http://ca.news.yahoo.com/s/capress/091230/national/afghan_cda_reporter |title=Condolence messages pouring in for reporter killed in Afghanistan |publisher=Canadian Press |date=30 December 2009 |accessdate=2009-12-31}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> when the armoured military vehicle she was riding in struck a roadside bomb.<ref name="canakia-CBCNEWS">{{cite news | url=http://www.cbc.ca/world/story/2009/12/30/kandahar-soldiers.html | title=5 Canadians killed in Afghanistan | publisher=[[CBC News]] | date=30 December 2009 | accessdate=2009-12-31 }}</ref> She died of her wounds and four Canadian soldiers were killed in the blast.<ref>[http://wardiary.wikileaks.org/afg/event/2009/12/AFG20091230n2384.html IED EXPLOSION RPT (RCIED) CANADIAN PRT : 4 CF KIA 5 CF WIA 1 CIV KIA]</ref>
She was survived by her fiancÃ©, Michael Louie.<ref name="National Post">{{cite news | url=http://www.nationalpost.com/news/story.html?id=2397416 | title=Calgary man mourns fiance lost to Taliban bomb | publisher=[[National Post]] | date=31 December 2009 | accessdate=2010-07-18 }}</ref>
